Historical trends, with few exceptions, are strongly in favor of the Republicans take the Senate. Taking a close look at the top ten race, it could be close, but still strongly favors Republicans taking the Senate. - Pennsylvania (open) - Democrats my be excited about the prospect of picking up outgoing Republican Toomey's seat, but they need to remember history. Toomey initially won the seat in 2010 (Obama's first mid-term) and reelection in 2016, which followed another general historical trend from the second half of the 20th Century, after eight years of a President of one party, a President of the other party follows (notable exception, George W. H. Bush following Reagan). In comparison is former Republican Senator Rick Santroum. He was first elected in the Republican wave of 1994 (Clinton's first mid-term), re-elected in 2000 (Presidency switched parties after eight years), and lost re-election in 2006 (George W. Bush's second mid-term). If following historical trends, 2022 will be more akin to 1994 and 2010. Republican hold the seat. - Georgia (incumbent seeking re-election) - Republicans certainly have a long term problems in Georgia, but the short term remains favorable towards them, especially in a mid-term. One should not forget, it was only just over twenty years ago that both Georgia Senators were Democrats. The Governor's race will also have a certainly have an impact in the Senate race. This is probably, at least at the moment, a true toss-up with the slightest of leans towards the Republicans. - Wisconsin (incumbent, unsure if he seeking re-election) - This state has ever-so-slowly been trending Republican for about two decades, but generally rebuffed by the growth of the Madison Area. Outside of Madison and Milwaukie, the state is extreme red, which was not the case twenty years ago. The question in Wisconsin is always minority turnout in Milwaukie. Johnson runs again, Republicans hold the seat, in part because of the same electoral history as Toomey. Open seat, leans Republicans depending on the parties nominees. - Arizona (incumbent, seeking re-election) - There are two factors in this race: 1) how much money does Kelley raise; and 2) who is the Republican nominee. The Republicans failure in the past two elections was mainly the result of having a horrible candidate in McSally. Despite McSally, she still narrowly lost in 2018 and significantly closer than the polls expected in 2020. There are certainly worse candidates than McSally in the Arizona. If Republican nominate the right candidate, this a hard fought Republican pickup. - Nevada (incumbent, seeking re-election) - This state has become a state where Republican only seem to be able to pick up seats in a Democratic President's midterm (Heller in 2012) or when Presidency switches parties (Ensign in 2000, who did win re-election in 2006, against a highly flawed candidate). The Republicans are putting up an extremally strong candidate this year and early polling has him slightly leading. Given the trends, this is probably a Republican pickup. - North Carolina (open) - As we move further down the list, the historical trend really kicks in. North Carolina, more so most states in recent history, follows the wave. The only mistake the Republicans could make in this state is nominating a weak candidate, but the Democrats have the same problem. Republican will be favored to hold this seat. - New Hampshire (incumbent, seeking re-election) - New Hampshire is moving away from its swing status. The right Republican candidate could win this seat, but those candidates have opted not to run. The race will probably be close, but a likely Democratic hold. - Florida (incumbent, seeking re-election) - At some point, Democrats need to realize that Florida has moved out of their reach. Yes, with the perfect candidates and in the right year, they could might win, but this is not the year, nor do the Democrats have the right candidate. The Senate and Governor races always seem close, but do not forget the size of the population in Florida. A four point victory is not close in the state. Additionally, the margin of Republican victories in the state have been fairly consistent, in not slightly growing. Florida is a Republican hold. - Ohio (open) - As an Ohioan, I can confidently confirm that Ohio is no longer a swing state. Also, having followed Congressman Tim Ryan's career, he does not have what it takes to wage a competitive race in the state, nor the ability to raise money. Even if the Republican Party nominates a weak candidate, the historical trend will ensure a Republican hold. - Missouri (open) - More so than Ohio, Missouri is no longer a swing state. Easy Republican hold. There are a couple of other states worth watching. Alaska could emerge as an opportunity for Democrats if a three-way race emerges, with Murkowski running as an independent. Colorado is becoming increasingly polarized, Denver vs. the rest of the state. Kansas has been showing a distain for extremely conservative candidates and some odd trends. Iowa, even though moving to the right, is Iowa, who knows what might happen there. However, at this moment, I predict a Senate with 52 or 53 Republicans come 2023.

There are 34 seats up for elections: 14 Democrats and 20 Republicans. Right now the Senate is 50-50 with the VPOTUS as the tiebreaker. During the previous election, 14 Republicans won their seats by 10% or higher (70%), 8 for the Democrats (57%). The Democrats have only had control of Congress and the Presidency twice since 1990, the Republicans four times. Given Biden's ratings (currently ~42%, only 1% above Trump's avg rating) and discontent over mishandling of Afghan withdrawal, budget, and migrant issues, the advantage will likely go to the Republicans who will exploit those issues to regain control of the Senate.

Democrats have a few pickup opportunities in places like WI and PA, whereas Republicans seem poised to blow their main, easy chance at a pickup in GA by nominating Herschel Walker. That said, the demography of historical cycles is on the GOP's side. They could quite plausibly hold their current seats and still pickup GA, and/or AZ. The main reason I'm not giving the Rs the overwhelming advantage of historical cycles that they had in, say, 2010 is because the higher-turnout demographics (white-collar, suburban professionals) have inched "bluer" in recent years and a 50-50 wash implies the Senate remains in Democratic hands given a Democratic VPOTUS. Further, Trump's unpopularity with a large chunk of Indpendents as the clear continued leader of his party could be a contributing factor to modestly stronger (compared to 2010) showings for Dems.
